long_desc.thetext:
We are setting a new appearance for a widget after this widget already has been displayd.
The problem is that the new appearance will not be displayd.

We have debugged through the source code of qooxdoo and found a possible reason for this problem:
The problem is in the Method qx.ui.core.Widget.syncAppearance:
      if (this.__updateSelector)
      {
        // Check if the selector was created previously
        if (selector)
        {
          // Query old selector
          var oldData = manager.styleFrom(selector, states, null, this.getAppearance());

          if (oldData) {
            selector = null;
          }
        }
      }


In our case, the variable "selector" contains the name of the old appearance, the variable "this.getAppearance()" returns the name of the new appearance.
Therefore the first parameter of the call to "manager.styleForm()" contains the old appearance name and the last parameter contains the new appearance name.
Therefore the variable "oldData" will be null.
Therefore the variable "selector" will not be set to null, but will keep containing the old appearance name.

For test purposes, we have changed the code so that the variable "selected" is always set to null, and not only if "oldData" is not null.
This change of the code did fix the problem.

I would recommend to change the code in qx.ui.core.Widget.syncAppearance from:

      if (this.__updateSelector)
      {
        // Clear flag
        delete this.__updateSelector;

        // Check if the selector was created previously
        if (selector)
        {
          // Query old selector
          var oldData = manager.styleFrom(selector, states, null, this.getAppearance());

          if (oldData) {
            selector = null;
          }
          selector = null;
        }
      }

To:

      if (this.__updateSelector)
      {
        // Clear flag
        delete this.__updateSelector;

        selector = null;
      }

I have written a stand-alone program that demonstrated the problem.
This program can be found in the attachment changeappearancedemo.zip.

The problem can be explained with the help of the attached screenshot "AppearanceDemoScreenshot.png".
The program creates two message widgets, the first message widget has the appearance "errormessage" and the second message widget has the appearance "confirmationmessage".
The button "Change Appearance" changes the appearance of the second message widget from "confirmationmessage" to "errormessage".
After this appearance has been changed, both message widget have exactly the same appearancy, but look differently.

The cause of this bug is probably located in the method qx.core.ui.Widget.syncAppearance:
      if (this.__updateSelector) {
        delete this.__updateSelector;
        if (selector) {
          var oldData = manager.styleFrom(
                            selector, states, null, this.getAppearance());
          if (oldData) {
            selector = null;
          }
        }
      }
The problem probably can be fixed by changing to code to:
      if (this.__updateSelector) {
        delete this.__updateSelector;
        selector = null;
      }

Thanks for the fix.

I reopen this issue to recommend a performance improvement:

The old code (in class qx.ui.core.Widget) was:
          var oldData = manager.styleFrom(...);

          // Clear current selector (to force recompute)
          if (oldData) {
            selector = null;
          }
The fixed code is now:
          var oldData = manager.styleFrom(...);

          selector = null;

I recommend to remove the line "oldData = manager.styleFrom".
The variable oldData is now not used anymore, and the call "manager.styleFrom" takes a lot of time.

